<div id="review_2791553507" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2791553507" />
    <a title="Kim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11161028-kim"><img alt="Kim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1562512310p2/11161028.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2791553507?book_show_action=true">Jul 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kim" href="/user/show/11161028-kim">Kim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141391540" href="/book/show/15925013-bastard-out-of-carolina">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2791553507" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14640581294148374343">Setting: South Carolina, USA; 1950s. This is the moving, raw and poignant tale of Ruth Anna Boatwright, known to her family as &apos;Bone&apos;, raised in a &apos;poor white trash&apos; family in South Carolina, the tale being narrated by herself. <br/>Her mother was fifteen when she gave birth to Bone and her father is unknown, hence the title of the book. Despite their comparative poverty, Bone leads a happy life with a network of aunts and uncles who sometimes provide a stabilising influence and sometimes much drama.</span>
  <span id="freeText14640581294148374343" style="display:none">Setting: South Carolina, USA; 1950s. This is the moving, raw and poignant tale of Ruth Anna Boatwright, known to her family as 'Bone', raised in a 'poor white trash' family in South Carolina, the tale being narrated by herself. <br />Her mother was fifteen when she gave birth to Bone and her father is unknown, hence the title of the book. Despite their comparative poverty, Bone leads a happy life with a network of aunts and uncles who sometimes provide a stabilising influence and sometimes much drama. Bone also has a younger sister, Reece, by a man her mother adored but who was killed in a road traffic accident. Hence, the three of them struggle along on their own.<br />But local man Glen Waddell, whose father owns the local creamery, has his eyes set on Bone's mother and soon worms his way into her affections. All seems fine until it becomes clear that Bone is a constant antagonism to Glen, despite all her efforts, and her joyous world becomes one of fear and exile from all that she knows....<br />This was a wonderfully gripping read, all the more so after reading the afterword when it becomes clear that the story is partly autobiographical - a disturbing and thought-provoking read. The afterword also refers to the author joining the fight against censorship in schools, who wanted to be able to refuse to allow books to be read by students - a teacher in a Maine school who she supported in her fight to have the book listed as a set book actually lost her job over the incident when parents objected to their children reading something so uncomfortable!<br />This was very nearly a 5 star read for me but not quite - 4.5 stars and 9+/10.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14640581294148374343" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


